    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4029721448" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4029721448" />
    <a title="❀ Crystal ✿ -  PEACE ☮ LOVE ♥ BOOKS " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10734393-crystal---peace-love-books"><img alt="❀ Crystal ✿ -  PEACE ☮ LOVE ♥ BOOKS " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1396916584p2/10734393.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4029721448?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="❀ Crystal ✿ -  PEACE ☮ LOVE ♥ BOOKS " class="user" itemprop="url" name="❀ Crystal ✿ -  PEACE ☮ LOVE ♥ BOOKS " href="/user/show/10734393-crystal---peace-love-books">❀ Crystal ✿ -  PEACE ☮ LOVE ♥ BOOKS </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10734393-crystal---peace-love-books?shelf=2021-read-list">2021-read-list</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4029721448" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer65835612856432432">This book was very well written and extremely action packed keeping me on the edge of my seat wanting answers. I realize it&apos;s part of a trilogy within the series and perhaps that&apos;s why by the end it feels so incomplete. It was quite a shock to learn not only was Pendergast married but to learn of the demise of his wife years ago during a safari trip. It&apos;s been over ten years since her death and for whatever reason Pendergast examines the shotgun she used that fateful day to try and kill a stalki</span>
  <span id="freeText65835612856432432" style="display:none">This book was very well written and extremely action packed keeping me on the edge of my seat wanting answers. I realize it's part of a trilogy within the series and perhaps that's why by the end it feels so incomplete. It was quite a shock to learn not only was Pendergast married but to learn of the demise of his wife years ago during a safari trip. It's been over ten years since her death and for whatever reason Pendergast examines the shotgun she used that fateful day to try and kill a stalking lion. Upon examination of the weapon Pendergast notes one of the spent shells was actually a blank meaning only one thing, his wife's death was not an accident but instead murder. Following an extremely cold trail Pendergast inquires the help of D'Gosta once again and the two set off on a worldwide scavenger hunt picking up clues and any information that they can. Seems Pendergast's wife had more secrets than even he did and even their random meeting at an art gallery was no accident. There's so many open threads that I imagine will continue on in the series and I'm dying to find out what the hell is going on. I loved seeing old characters like D'Gosta and Hayward take on larger roles within the books once again but I can't lie and say I wasn't deathly afraid one or both would be hurt. While Pendergast is extremely intelligent and good at what he does, it's unfortunate that many involved with him end up dead! There's another side story with Constance that I'm trying to piece together and I can't wait to see what's going on with her now that she-like Pendergast once upon a time has wound up in a mental institution. Not only that but in previous books Pendergast had a burgeoning relationship and now I don't know where that stands. So many questions and I'm so into this series at this point I can't wait to see where it takes us next!</span>
  <a data-text-id="65835612856432432" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


